PART I: THE B-MATRIX ROTATION VIEW
========================================================================

The sine matrix B[t,j] = sin(2ПЂjt/p) maps Пѓ в€€ {В±1}^m to b в€€ R^{p-1}.
Since B has all singular values = в€љ(p/4), the mapping Пѓ в†’ b = BПѓ
is a SCALED ROTATION.

The degree-4 Walsh coefficient ДҐ[{i,j,k,l}] can be written as:
  ДҐ[S] = (1/2^m) ОЈ_Пѓ HМѓ(BПѓ) В· Пѓ_i Пѓ_j Пѓ_k Пѓ_l

where HМѓ is the function that maps eigenvalue imaginary parts to H.

In the B-coordinates:
  Пѓ_i = ОЈ_t BвЂ [i,t] b_t / (p/4)   (pseudo-inverse)

So the product Пѓ_i Пѓ_j Пѓ_k Пѓ_l involves a sum over 4 eigenvalue indices.

The CONTINUOUS approximation (valid for large m):
  ДҐ[{i,j,k,l}] в‰€ (4/p)^4 ОЈ_{tв‚Ѓ,tв‚‚,tв‚ѓ,tв‚„} B[tв‚Ѓ,i]B[tв‚‚,j]B[tв‚ѓ,k]B[tв‚„,l]
                    Г— (в€‚вЃґHМѓ/в€‚b_{tв‚Ѓ}в€‚b_{tв‚‚}в€‚b_{tв‚ѓ}в€‚b_{tв‚„})

This connects the Walsh coefficient to the 4th-order sensitivity of H
to eigenvalue perturbations!

